<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Heights and Terrain
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to sculpt terrain by raising, lowering, levelling, and flattening height vertices.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Enabling the Heights Layer
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Heights layer is
        <Bold>switched off by default</Bold> . To enable it, either press
        <Bold>Ctrl+H</Bold> or click the
        <Bold>Heights</Bold> button in the Terrain group of
        the layer toolbar at the top of the screen.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/heights_layer_toggle.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        Understanding Vertices
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        It is important to understand that when editing heights, you are modifying the
        <Bold>vertices</Bold> (corners) of cells, not the cells themselves. Each tile on the
        128 x 128 grid has four corner vertices, shared with its neighbouring tiles. This creates
        a 129 x 129 vertex grid that defines the shape of the terrain surface.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        When the Heights layer is enabled, each vertex appears as a
        <Bold>circle</Bold> displaying
        an integer value representing the current height at that point. A value of
        <Bold>0</Bold>
        means the vertex is at the baseline (flat ground). Positive values raise the terrain
        upward and negative values lower it, with a range of -128 to 127.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/heights_vertex_circles.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Colour Coding
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The vertex circles are colour-coded to give you an at-a-glance view of the terrain shape:
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,6,0,0">
        <Bold Foreground="#7AD7FF">Blue</Bold> -- low values (valleys, ditches, depressions)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,2,0,0">
        <Bold Foreground="#FFFFFF">White</Bold> -- zero (flat baseline)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,2,0,0">
        <Bold Foreground="#2EB84A">Green</Bold> -- high values (hills, ridges, elevated areas)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        When you hover over a vertex with a height tool selected, the circle turns
        <Bold Foreground="#E50000">red</Bold> to indicate the target vertex.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Height Editing Controls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Heights tab in the editor drawer contains all of the tools for terrain editing.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/heights_editor_tab.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Units
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The
        <Bold>Units</Bold> box controls how many height units are applied per click. For
        example, with Units set to 1, each click on a vertex raises or lowers it by 1. Setting
        a higher value allows you to make larger changes more quickly. The height range is -128
        to 127, so each unit represents a small step in elevation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Brush Size
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The
        <Bold>Brush Size</Bold> determines the area affected by each click, ranging from
        1 to 10. A brush size of 1 affects a single vertex (1x1), while a size of 10 affects a
        10x10 area of vertices centred on the click point. Larger brush sizes are useful for
        creating smooth, gradual terrain features like hills, while smaller sizes give you
        fine-grained control for detailed sculpting.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Actions
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Raise</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Click on a vertex to increase its height by the number specified
        in the Units box. Each click adds the unit value to the current height. The affected area
        is determined by the current brush size.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Lower</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Click on a vertex to decrease its height by the number specified
        in the Units box. Each click subtracts the unit value from the current height.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Level</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Click on a vertex to sample its height value, then drag across
        other vertices to set them all to the same height. The first vertex clicked determines
        the target height, and every vertex you drag over is set to that value. This is useful
        for creating flat platforms or extending an existing height across an area.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Flatten</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Click on a vertex to reset it to 0 (flat baseline). This is a
        quick way to remove height changes and return the terrain to its default flat state.</Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/heights_raise_lower_example.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Set Height Area by Drag
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For situations where you need to set a large number of vertices to a specific height
        value, use the
        <Bold>Set Height Area</Bold> tool. First, enter the desired height value
        in the input box. Then click the
        <Bold>Drag Area</Bold> button and draw a rectangle over
        the vertices you want to modify. All vertices within the rectangle will be set to the
        specified value.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is particularly useful for creating flat elevated platforms, uniform depressions,
        or quickly preparing an area for building placement where consistent terrain height
        is required.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/heights_drag_area.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Stamps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Stamps</Bold> section lets you apply pre-built vertex height patterns to
        the map. Stamps are fully user-created and can be saved to disk for reuse across
        sessions and shared between maps.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/heights_stamps_list.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Applying a Stamp
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Placing a stamp is a three-step process:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Choose a stamp from the <Bold>dropdown list</Bold> in the Stamps panel.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click the <Bold>Stamp</Bold> button to arm the tool. The cursor changes to
                indicate stamp placement mode is active.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click the desired location on the map canvas. The stamp's height pattern is
                applied immediately, centred on the clicked vertex.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph>
        There is no hover preview — the stamp is placed on the first click after the button is
        activated. If you place it in the wrong spot, use <Bold>Ctrl+Z</Bold> to undo and try
        again.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        The Stamp Editor
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Click the <Bold>+ New Stamp</Bold> button in the Stamps panel to open the Stamp Editor.
        Creating a stamp is a four-step process:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Type the desired grid size into the size box and click
                <Bold>Generate Grid</Bold>. A blank grid of that size appears, ready to fill.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click each cell in the grid and enter a height value between
                <Bold>-127</Bold> and <Bold>127</Bold>. Negative values lower the terrain;
                positive values raise it; zero leaves the vertex at ground level.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Give the stamp a name.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click <Bold>Save Stamp</Bold>. The stamp is written as a
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.stamp.json</Run> file to the
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">CustomStamps</Run> folder next
                to the editor executable and immediately appears in the dropdown list.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <!-- IMAGE NEEDED: heights_stamp_editor.png — the Stamp Editor window showing the grid size input, Generate Grid button, the filled cell grid, name field and Save Stamp button -->
        <Border Background="#2A2A2A" BorderBrush="#555" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/heights_stamp_editor.png"
       MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph>
        Custom stamps persist between sessions. You can manage them directly in the
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">CustomStamps</Run> folder —
        delete, rename, or copy
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.stamp.json</Run> files as needed.
        The dropdown refreshes automatically when the panel is next opened.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Randomize Terrain
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Randomize</Bold> button applies a procedural algorithm to generate realistic
        terrain heights across the entire map. This produces natural-looking hills, valleys, and
        undulating ground that can serve as a starting point for further manual sculpting. It
        affects all 129 x 129 vertices at once.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/heights_randomized.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Warning:</Run>
                <Run>Randomize overwrites all height values on the map. If you have existing terrain work, save your map first or use it only on a fresh map.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Randomize Area
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Instead of randomizing the whole map at once, you can target a specific region with
        the <Bold>Randomize Area</Bold> tool. Click the <Bold>Randomize Area</Bold> button,
        then click and drag on the canvas to draw a rectangle around the vertices you want
        to affect. When you release the mouse, the algorithm runs only within that rectangle,
        leaving the rest of the map untouched.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/heights_randomize_area.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Randomize Constraints
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Three optional constraints let you control the character of the generated terrain.
        All three apply to both the full-map Randomize and the Randomize Area tool:
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Max Height</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">Sets a ceiling on how high any vertex within the randomized
        region can be raised. Vertices will not exceed this value regardless of what the
        algorithm generates. Leave blank (or set to 127) to impose no upper limit.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Max Depth</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">Sets a floor on how low any vertex can be pushed. Vertices
        will not go below the negative of this value. Leave blank (or set to 128) to impose
        no lower limit. For example, a Max Depth of 10 means no vertex will be lower
        than -10.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Max Slope</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">Limits the maximum height difference allowed between any two
        adjacent vertices in the randomized region. This prevents cliff faces and sharp spikes,
        producing smoother, more gradual terrain. A lower value gives rounder hills; a higher
        value allows steeper drops.</Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/heights_randomize_constraints.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Tips
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Zoom in with
                <Bold>Ctrl+Mouse Wheel</Bold> for precise vertex editing. At high zoom levels, individual vertices are easier to target.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use a small brush size (1 or 2) for detailed work around buildings and paths, and a larger brush (5-10) for broad landscape shaping.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>The
                <Bold>Level</Bold> tool is excellent for creating flat building sites -- raise one vertex to the desired height, then level-drag across the surrounding area.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Keep terrain changes gradual where possible. Sharp height differences between adjacent vertices can create visual artefacts in-game.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Heights are independent of textures -- you can paint textures before or after sculpting terrain. Both are saved together in the .iam file.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Remember that buildings and prims sit on top of the terrain surface. If you change heights after placing buildings, the walls may no longer align with the ground. Adjust facet Y0/Y1 values if needed.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use <Bold>Randomize Area</Bold> instead of full-map Randomize to add organic variation to a specific neighbourhood without disturbing carefully crafted terrain elsewhere.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Set a low <Bold>Max Slope</Bold> value (e.g. 3–5) when randomizing areas that will contain roads or buildings to keep the generated terrain walkable and buildable.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Build a library of reusable <Bold>Stamps</Bold> for common shapes — hills, craters, river banks, ramps — and apply them quickly anywhere on the map. Stamps scale with the Units value, so one stamp can serve multiple height ranges.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
